  "signature": "ed25519:6c5f1f75c9a8c4de8d6aa59a48d851d7ef346e5663925db6bbce61d2c1b85500ce9731a1fb6e19913bffd995e4092dcc26d467442b03e545e48500d31fa95808",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-sqa-criteria",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house solver, Ansys Mechanical 2022R2, DePuy Synthes internal solver) operate under documented software quality assurance programs. FDA in-house solver is governed by an ISO 9001-compliant SQA plan with version control, regression testing, and change control records. Ansys Mechanical is a commercially validated code with published verification and validation documentation. DePuy Synthes internal solver is subject to a 21 CFR Part 820-aligned software validation protocol. Achieved Gradation 3: each code has documented SQA procedures, version-controlled releases, and traceable test suites covering the relevant physics. Required Gradation 2 for Medium model risk, Medium model influence context."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-ncv-criteria",
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification for all three ensemble codes was confirmed through benchmark problems relevant to structural mechanics of metallic implants: cantilever beam bending, contact mechanics patch tests, and large-deformation elastoplastic cylinder compression. Each code reproduced analytical or reference solutions within 0.5% for linear problems and within 2% for nonlinear contact problems. Ansys Mechanical verification is documented in the ANSYS Mechanical Verification Manual (Release 2022R2). FDA solver verification is documented in internal report FDA-OSEL-SV-2019-07. DePuy Synthes solver verification is documented in DS-FEA-VER-2020-003. Achieved Gradation 2 meets the required level for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-discretization-criteria",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were performed for all three FEA models using three successive mesh refinements (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation was applied to stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm QoIs. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for the fine mesh solution was below 1.2% for all three QoIs across all three codes, confirming that discretization error is well-characterized and below the 2% threshold established in the acceptance criteria. Contact regions at the screw-rod interface and screw-vertebral body block interface used local refinement with element size ≤0.1 mm. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects the quantified GCI and documented convergence study."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-solver-error-criteria",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence was monitored for all nonlinear analyses. Force residual and displacement residual norms were converged to below 1×10⁻⁴ relative tolerance for each load step. Time-stepping sensitivity was confirmed by halving the load increment size and observing less than 0.3% change in all QoIs. Contact penetration was confirmed to be below 0.001 mm at all interfaces at final load state. These checks are documented in the analysis control files archived in the project repository. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds the required Gradation 1 for this factor at Medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-use-error-criteria",
      "rationale": "All three modeling teams followed a pre-specified simulation protocol document (SPD-COU1-v2.1) that defined mesh strategy, material assignment, boundary condition application, contact formulation, and output extraction procedures. Independent peer review of each team's model setup was conducted by a reviewer not involved in model construction. Discrepancies identified during peer review were resolved prior to execution of production runs. Model setup checklists were completed and archived for each of the three codes. Achieved Gradation 2 reflects the documented protocol, independent review, and traceable setup records."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-model-form-criteria",
      "rationale": "The continuum FEA model form was selected based on established precedent for metallic spinal implant structural analysis. Titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) was modeled as bilinear elastoplastic with isotropic hardening, with material constants derived from ASTM E8 tensile coupon testing of the same lot material used for experimental specimens. The UHMWPE vertebral body block surrogate was modeled as linear elastic based on published characterization data and confirmed appropriate for the displacement regime of interest (below 50 mm). Frictional contact (μ=0.2, penalty formulation) was used at all interfaces, consistent with published literature for Ti-UHMWPE contact pairs. Sensitivity analyses confirmed that ±20% variation in friction coefficient produced less than 3% change in QoIs. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects the documented model form justification, sensitivity analysis, and literature support."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-model-inputs-criteria",
      "rationale": "All model inputs were derived from direct measurement of the test specimens and test fixtures used in the validation experiments. Screw and rod geometry was characterized by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) with ±0.005 mm accuracy; mean dimensions used in FEA models with uncertainty bounds propagated via Monte Carlo sampling (N=1000 draws). Material properties (elastic modulus, yield strength, tangent modulus) were measured from tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock as the screws. UHMWPE block modulus was measured by compression testing per ASTM D695. Fixture dimensions were measured from the actual test fixtures used in both laboratories. Input uncertainty contributions were quantified and incorporated into the validation uncertainty budget. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects direct measurement traceability and quantified input uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-test-samples-criteria",
      "rationale": "N=11 experimental constructs were assembled and tested across two independent laboratories (FDA OSEL biomechanics laboratory, n=6; DePuy Synthes testing laboratory, n=5). All screws and rods were sourced from a single production lot with documented dimensional inspection records. UHMWPE vertebral body block surrogates were machined to ASTM F1717 specification from a single billet with density and modulus verification. Inter-laboratory reproducibility was assessed: coefficient of variation for stiffness across labs was 4.1%, for yield force 5.3%, and for force at 40 mm 6.0%, all within acceptable limits. Sample size of N=11 provides sufficient statistical power to characterize experimental mean and standard deviation for uncertainty quantification. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects the multi-laboratory design, lot traceability, and inter-laboratory reproducibility assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "The Test conditions factor evaluates whether the range of experimental test conditions used in the validation activity adequately spans the conditions relevant to the COU, and whether sensitivity to test condition variation has been characterized. For this COU, ASTM F1717 specifies a single standardized test configuration: static compression-bending at a fixed offset distance (50 mm) with displacement control at 5 mm/min, in ambient laboratory conditions. The protocol does not permit variation of loading rate, offset distance, or environmental conditions within a single F1717 compliance study, as the standard is explicitly designed to produce a single-condition comparative benchmark. Scoping out this factor is therefore justified on the following grounds: (1) The COU is specifically and exclusively defined as prediction of ASTM F1717 standard test performance — the model is not claimed to generalize beyond this single standardized condition, and no regulatory submission relies on extrapolation to other loading conditions from this model. (2) The regulatory context (510(k) substantial equivalence for a Class II device) does not require demonstration of multi-condition robustness for the F1717 compression-bending QoIs; the single-condition result is the accepted regulatory evidence standard. (3) Sensitivity to test condition variation (loading rate, offset distance) is addressed in a separate, higher-fidelity COU (COU3: parametric loading sensitivity) that is outside the scope of this credibility assessment. (4) The ASME V&V 40-2018 standard explicitly permits scoping out factors where the factor is not applicable to the defined scope of the validation activity, provided that the scope limitation is documented and the decision context does not require the factor. The decision consequence is Medium and model influence is Medium; the resulting model risk level of 3 does not mandate multi-condition test coverage for a standardized compliance test COU. This scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team and is documented in assessment record CA-COU1-2024-003."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-input-equivalency-criteria",
      "rationale": "A systematic parameter equivalency mapping was performed to confirm that each model input parameter has a directly corresponding measured experimental quantity. The mapping table (document EQ-COU1-v1.3) covers 23 input parameters across geometry, material, boundary conditions, and contact. For each parameter, the experimental measurement method, measurement uncertainty, and the FEA input value with its uncertainty bound are documented. No model input was assigned a value not traceable to a direct measurement of the validation specimens or fixtures. Parameters that could not be directly measured (e.g., residual stress state) were confirmed to have negligible sensitivity (< 0.5% QoI change) through perturbation analysis and are documented as justified assumptions. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects the complete parameter mapping, traceability, and sensitivity confirmation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-output-comparison-criteria",
      "rationale": "Quantitative output comparison was performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement). The validation uncertainty uval was computed as the root-sum-square of experimental uncertainty (inter-specimen variability, inter-laboratory variability, measurement system uncertainty) and numerical uncertainty (discretization error GCI, solver convergence error, input parameter uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo). Results: stiffness E/uval = 0.87 (acceptance bound: < 1.96); yield force E/uval = 1.31 (< 1.96); force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.54 (< 1.96). All three QoIs pass the pre-established acceptance criterion. Percentage differences are 4.2%, 6.8%, and 7.3% respectively, all within the <10% bound. Comparison was performed blind: experimental results were withheld from modeling teams until all FEA runs were completed and locked. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects the quantitative metric, blind comparison protocol, and complete uncertainty budget."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-qoi-relevance-criteria",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs — construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement — are the primary mechanical performance metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and are the quantities used in the regulatory submission to demonstrate substantial equivalence. Construct stiffness characterizes the elastic load-bearing behavior of the screw-rod system. Yield force identifies the onset of permanent deformation, which is the primary failure mode of concern for clinical use. Force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield load-carrying capacity relevant to catastrophic failure assessment. All three QoIs are directly output by the FEA model and directly measured in the experimental protocol. The mapping between model QoIs and clinical/regulatory decision QoIs is documented in the COU definition (document COU1-DEF-v2.0). Achieved Gradation 2 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/nagaraja-cou1-validation-relevance-criteria",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same FEA modeling framework, the same device geometry, the same material lot, the same test protocol (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending), and the same QoIs are used in both the validation activity and the intended regulatory application. The validation specimens are from the same production lot as the devices to be submitted. The two-laboratory design increases confidence that the validation result is not an artifact of a single laboratory's equipment or technique. The only difference between the validation activity and the COU application is that the COU application will use the model predictively for a design variant (cannulated version, COU2); however, COU1 is defined exclusively as the non-cannulated validation and does not claim predictive relevance to the cannulated design. The validation-to-COU relevance is therefore essentially complete for COU1. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects the high fidelity of correspondence between validation conditions and COU conditions."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw ASTM F1717 compression-bending FEA prediction) is accepted based on the following structured evidence review. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 factors were assessed; one factor (Test conditions) was scoped out with documented justification appropriate to the single-condition ASTM F1717 protocol and the defined COU scope. Of the twelve assessed factors, all achieved levels meet or exceed required levels for a Model Risk Level 3 (Medium model influence, Medium decision consequence) context. The three primary QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) all satisfy the pre-established quantitative acceptance criteria: E/uval < 1.96 and percentage difference < 10%. The validation was conducted as a blind comparison across three independent FEA codes and two independent experimental laboratories, providing strong evidence of model credibility that is not dependent on any single analyst or laboratory. The uncertainty budget is complete and traceable, incorporating experimental variability (inter-specimen, inter-laboratory, measurement system), numerical uncertainty (discretization GCI, solver convergence), and input parameter uncertainty (Monte Carlo propagation). The scoping of the Test conditions factor is appropriate and documented: the COU is defined exclusively as prediction of the standardized ASTM F1717 single-condition test, multi-condition generalization is not claimed, and the regulatory decision context does not require it. No weakeners were identified in this package. The credibility assessment team concludes that the FEA modeling framework has sufficient credibility for its intended use in the COU1 regulatory submission context.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
